In the sprawling, often tedious world of [mathematics](/Mathematic), the **Hessian matrix**—also known simply as the Hessian or, if you're feeling archaic, the Hesse matrix—emerges as a fundamental tool. It is, put simply, a [square matrix](/Square_matrix) containing the second-order [partial derivatives](/Partial_derivative) of some scalar-valued [function](/Function_(mathematics)), or [scalar field](/Scalar_field). Its purpose is to describe the local [curvature](/Curvature) of a function with multiple variables, which is a concept you'd grasp if you ever looked up from a two-dimensional plane.

This particular mathematical construct was developed in the 19th century by the German mathematician [Ludwig Otto Hesse](/Otto_Hesse), and was subsequently named after him. Hesse, with a flair for the dramatic, originally called them "functional determinants." The Hessian is sometimes denoted with an almost comical variety of symbols, including H, 
