However, computing and storing the full Hessian matrix demands `Θ(n^2)` memory. This is completely infeasible for high-dimensional functions, such as the [loss functions](/Loss_function) of [neural nets](/Artificial_neural_network), [conditional random fields](/Conditional_random_field), and other complex [statistical models](/Statistical_model) with an absurd number of parameters. For these situations, cleverer methods have been devised, such as [truncated-Newton](/Truncated_Newton_method) and [quasi-Newton](/Quasi-Newton_method) algorithms. The latter family of algorithms, which includes the popular [BFGS](/Broyden%E2%80%93Fletcher%E2%80%93Goldfarb%E2%80%93Shanno_algorithm) method, uses approximations of the Hessian to get the job done.

